CYBER GUARD — README
======================

A modular command-line cybersecurity utility built in Python.
Modules: Network Probe | Credential Auditor | System Log Inspector | Access Control Manager

----------------------------------------------------------
REQUIREMENTS
----------------------------------------------------------
- Python 3.7 or higher
- No external libraries needed (uses only built-in modules)

----------------------------------------------------------
QUICK START
----------------------------------------------------------
Step 1: Open terminal / VS Code integrated terminal
Step 2: Navigate to your project folder
        

Step 3: Run the showcase demo
        python cyber_guard.py showcase

----------------------------------------------------------
FEATURES & USAGE
----------------------------------------------------------

1. NETWORK PROBE
-----------------
Scans open TCP ports on a target host within a given range.

Command:
  python cyber_guard.py probe <target> --from <port> --to <port>

Example:
  python cyber_guard.py probe 192.168.1.1 --from 1 --to 1024

Output:
  [PROBE] Target: 192.168.1.1 | Range: 1-1024
  --------------------------------------------------
    OPEN     22  [ssh]
    OPEN     80  [http]
    OPEN    443  [https]
  --------------------------------------------------
  [PROBE] Done. 3 open port(s) detected.


2. CREDENTIAL AUDITOR
----------------------
Evaluates the strength of a password against 6 security rules.

Command:
  python cyber_guard.py audit "<password>"

Example:
  python cyber_guard.py audit "S3cur3P@ssw0rd#99"

Rules Checked:
  - Minimum 12 characters
  - Contains uppercase letter (A-Z)
  - Contains lowercase letter (a-z)
  - Contains number (0-9)
  - Contains symbol (!@#$% etc.)
  - Avoids weak patterns (pass, 1234, admin, login, etc.)

Rating Scale:
  6/6 --> EXCELLENT
  5/6 --> STRONG
  4/6 --> AVERAGE
  <4  --> POOR


3. SYSTEM LOG INSPECTOR
------------------------
Parses SSH authentication log files to detect threats and brute-force attacks.

Command:
  python cyber_guard.py inspect <logfile>

Example:
  python cyber_guard.py inspect auth.log

Note:
  - On Windows, create a local auth.log file for testing
  - On Linux/Mac, use: python cyber_guard.py inspect /var/log/auth.log

Detects:
  - Successful logins (username + IP address)
  - Failed login attempts (username + IP address)
  - IPs with 5 or more failed attempts flagged as THREAT DETECTED


4. ACCESS CONTROL MANAGER (Firewall)
--------------------------------------
Generates iptables firewall rules to deny an IP and permit specific ports.

Print rules to terminal:
  python cyber_guard.py acm --deny <IP> --permit <port1> <port2> ...

Save rules to a file:
  python cyber_guard.py acm --deny <IP> --save rules.sh

Examples:
  python cyber_guard.py acm --deny 10.0.0.99 --permit 22 80 443
  python cyber_guard.py acm --deny 10.0.0.99 --save rules.sh

Generated Rules Include:
  - Flush existing chains
  - DROP rules for the denied IP (INPUT + OUTPUT)
  - ACCEPT rules for permitted ports
  - Default policy: INPUT DROP, FORWARD DROP, OUTPUT ACCEPT


5. SHOWCASE (Demo Mode)
------------------------
Runs all modules with sample data to demonstrate the full toolkit.

Command:
  python cyber_guard.py showcase


----------------------------------------------------------
PROJECT STRUCTURE
----------------------------------------------------------
A28/
  |-- cyber_guard.py     
  |-- rules.sh           
  |-- README.txt         


----------------------------------------------------------
RUNNING IN VS CODE
----------------------------------------------------------
1. Open VS Code
2. Go to File > Open Folder and select your project folder
3. Press Ctrl + ` to open the integrated terminal
4. Terminal automatically opens in your project directory
5. Run commands directly without needing to cd

Correct way to run:
  python cyber_guard.py showcase
  python cyber_guard.py probe 192.168.1.1 --from 1 --to 1024
  python cyber_guard.py audit "YourPassword123!"
  python cyber_guard.py acm --deny 10.0.0.99 --permit 22 80 443


----------------------------------------------------------
COMMON ERRORS & FIXES
----------------------------------------------------------
Error : No such file or directory
Cause : Terminal not in the project folder
Fix   : Use VS Code integrated terminal 
        
Error : 'cyber_guard.py' is not recognized
Cause : Missing 'python' prefix in command
Fix   : Always use --> python cyber_guard.py ...

Error : python not found
Cause : Python not installed or not added to PATH
Fix   : Install Python 3.7+ from https://python.org
        During install, check "Add Python to PATH"

Error : File not found (for inspect command)
Cause : Log file does not exist at the given path
Fix   : Provide a valid local log file path


----------------------------------------------------------
MODULE SUMMARY
----------------------------------------------------------
  probe     -->  Scans network ports on a target host
  audit     -->  Checks password strength with 6 rules
  inspect   -->  Analyses auth logs for threats
  acm       -->  Generates iptables access control rules
  showcase  -->  Runs full demo of all features



